catalogue.definition:
Command for the aircraft data link communications. It allows the
GDLP to enable or disable the uplink & downlink data flows for a
specified aircraft.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - This command applies to the interrogator's
      Current status (UCS/DCS) and does not affect the
      interrogator’s Default Status (see UDS/DDS in
      Data Item I018/008).
catalogue.title: Aircraft Data Link Command

values: UC shall be ignored
UC shall be taken into account
DC shall be ignored
DC shall be taken into account
the uplink flow shall be enabled
the uplink flow shall be stopped
the downlink flow shall be enabled
the downlink flow shall be stopped

catalogue.definition: Status for the aircraft data link communications.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:
    1. The current status should never be more restrictive than the default status.
    2. IC is usually set 1when the interrogator is a member of a cluster with a
       decentralised data link responsibility protocol.
       IC is usually set to 0 when the interrogator is connected to a GDLP. IC
       settings shall comply with the rules defined in Ref.3.
catalogue.title: Aircraft Data Link Status

The interrogators current ability to uplink/downlink frames (UCS/DCS) and the content of the Aircraft_report cannot be changed using D_Data_link_command

      concern D_Data_link_status, D_COM, D_ECA, D_CQF, D_CQF_method,
      D_Polar_position, D_Cartesian_position, D_Aircraft_ID, D_Mode_A,
      D_Speed, D_Height, D_Heading.

catalogue.definition: Number used to correlate an uplink packet request and its associated acknowledgement.
catalogue.title: Packet Number

catalogue.definition: List of numbers used to correlate an uplink packet request and their associated acknowledgements
catalogue.title: Packet Number List

catalogue.definition:
Properties of an uplink Mode S packet, i.e. its internal priority and its capability to be
multiplexed or not, and its type (SVC, MSP or ROUTE).
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - The PT field is used to identify the ROUTE packets which have a higher
      priority than SVCs.  The PR field is used to describe the priority of SVCs as
      follows:

          0 = low
          1 = high

      For ROUTE and MSP packets the value of PR has no significance.  However,
      for the purpose of standardisation, it is recommended that for ROUTE
      packets, PR is set to 15 and for MSPs the PR should be set to 31.
catalogue.title: Mode S Packet Properties

values: SVC packets
MSP packets
Route packets

catalogue.definition: A Mode S packet as defined in the Mode S subnetwork SARPs.
catalogue.title: Mode S Packet

catalogue.definition: Number used to correlate an uplink broadcast request and its associated acknowledgement.
catalogue.title: Broadcast Number

catalogue.definition: Properties of an uplink broadcast request (power, duration, coverage).
catalogue.remark:
Notes:
     1. A broadcast with a higher priority will temporarily delay a lower priority broadcast if
        necessary. The delayed broadcast will be resumed as soon as possible for its
        remaining time.
     2. The sectors are numbered from 1 to 32 clockwise, sector 1 being the first sector after the North.
catalogue.title: Broadcast Properties

catalogue.definition: Contents of the 32 first bits of an uplink broadcast interrogation.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - The Mode S uplink broadcast interrogation will be made up of this
      D_Broadcast_prefix field followed by the D_Broadcast field and then by the
      Address/Parity field (in this order), as defined in ICAO Annex 10. In the
      interrogator, the 5 first bits of D_Broadcast_prefix will be replaced by ICAO
      UF field, as defined in Annex 10.
catalogue.title: Broadcast Prefix

catalogue.definition:
Broadcast message sent (MA field of the Comm-A frame) or received
(MB field of the Comm-B frame), conformant with the ICAO Manual on
Mode S Specific Services.
catalogue.title: Uplink or Downlink Broadcast

catalogue.title: BDS Code

catalogue.title: GICB Extracted

catalogue.definition: Properties of the GICB extractions.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - The Non Extraction flag (NE) should be used only if the Asynchronous
      Update flag (AU) is set to true. It is specially reserved to the ACAS' RA
      extraction (asynchronous update without periodic extraction request).
catalogue.title: GICB Properties

values: The periodicity may not be strictly respected
The periodicity shall be strictly respected
GICB extractions should be sent only when required by the periodicity
If a GICB extraction is done due to external conditions, an update will also be sent, even if it does not match the expected periodicity
The GICB extraction is attempted according to the periodicity
There will no GICB attempts
The extracted GICB must be sent only on the Data Link line
The extracted GICB must be sent only on the Surveillance line
The extracted GICB must be sent both on the Data Link and on the Surveillance lines

catalogue.definition: Identity of the aircraft extracted by a BDS 20 as described in ICAO Annex 10.
catalogue.title: Aircraft Identity

catalogue.definition: Mode-3/A code converted into octal representation.
catalogue.remark:
Note:
    - Bit 15 has no meaning in the case of a smoothed Mode-3/A code and is set
      to 0 for a calculated track. For Mode S, it is set to one when an error
      correction has been attempted.
catalogue.title: Aircraft Mode A

values: Code validated
Code not validated
Default
Garbled code
Mode-3/A code derived from the reply of the transponder
Mode-3/A code not extracted during the last scan

catalogue.definition: Flight Level converted into binary representation.
catalogue.remark:
Notes:
    1. The value shall be within the range described by ICAO Annex 10
    2. For Mode S, bit 15 (G) is set to one when an error correction
       has been attempted.
    3. If Altitude is not extracted on the last scan, it is an implementation
       issue as to whether Altitude is output from track file, if at all.
catalogue.title: Aircraft Height

values: Code validated
Code not validated
Default
Garbled code
